    <note type="source">Smith's Dictionary: "Nausiphanes, a native of Teos, attached to 
      the philosophy of Democritus, and, according to Sextus Empiricus, a disciple of 
      Pyrrhon. He had a large number of pupils, and was particularly famous as a rhetorician. 
      Epicurus was at one time one of his hearers, and as he could not deny this, though he was 
      anxious to be considered a self-taught man, he was obliged to content himself with abusing him, 
      and maintaining that he had learnt nothing from him....."</note>
